post_cb({"25709691": {"ParentId": "25709653", "CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2014-09-07T11:29:24.157", "Score": "0", "OwnerDisplayName": "user3414693", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "25709691", "OwnerUserId": "1501794", "Body": "<p>From the C++ standards:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_25709653_25709691_0\">An explicit specialization shall be declared in the namespace of which\n  the template is a member, or, for member templates, in the namespace\n  of which the enclosing class or enclosing class template is a member.\n  An explicit specialization of a member function, member class or\n  static data member of a class template shall be declared in the\n  namespace of which the class template is a member.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So you need to move the specialization outside  the scope of A's definition. You may try this:</p>\n<pre><code>class A\n{\n  template&lt;typename X, typename Y&gt;\n  void f()\n  { }\n};\ntemplate&lt;&gt;\nvoid A::f&lt;int, char&gt;()\n{ }\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-07T11:29:24.157", "LastEditorUserId": "1501794"}, "25709653": {"CommentCount": "2", "ViewCount": "121", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2014-09-07T11:29:23.877", "LastEditorUserId": "1413395", "CreationDate": "2014-09-07T11:22:43.023", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-07T11:29:24.157", "Title": "Explicit template specialization of member functions", "LastEditDate": "2014-09-07T11:26:13.823", "Id": "25709653", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>I have the following minimal example:</p>\n<pre><code>class A\n{\n  template&lt;typename X, typename Y&gt;\n  void f()\n  { }\n\n  template&lt;&gt;\n  void f&lt;int, char&gt;()\n  { }\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>The compiler gives an error message </p>\n<pre><code> explicit specialzation in non-namespace scope.\n</code></pre>\n<p>Why is this wrong and how can I fix it?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><templates>", "OwnerUserId": "2683038", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "25709686": {"ParentId": "25709653", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>\u00a714.7.3 [temp.expl.spec]/p2:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_25709653_25709686_0\">An explicit specialization shall be declared in a namespace enclosing the specialized template.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So you need to move the specialization outside <code>A</code>'s definition:</p>\n<pre><code>class A\n{\n  template&lt;typename X, typename Y&gt;\n  void f()\n  { }\n};\n\ntemplate&lt;&gt;\nvoid A::f&lt;int, char&gt;()\n{ }\n</code></pre>\n", "OwnerUserId": "2756719", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "25709686", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-09-07T11:28:22.140", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-07T11:28:22.140"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_25709653_25709686_0": {"section_id": 264, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}, "so_25709653_25709691_0": {"section_id": 150, "quality": 0.5806451612903226, "length": 18}}, "n3337": {"so_25709653_25709686_0": {"section_id": 255, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}, "so_25709653_25709691_0": {"section_id": 144, "quality": 0.5806451612903226, "length": 18}}, "n4659": {"so_25709653_25709686_0": {"section_id": 285, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_25709653_25709691_0": {"section_id": 154, "quality": 0.5806451612903226, "length": 18}}}});